John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and it continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which is only reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Council (SCIS), strive to deliver the best possible level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, for their chosen career and for their role as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages remain a popular and desirable choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak a man in a language that he understands, he will understand with his mind.
If he speaks in his own language, he will understand with his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's recent examinations, we can see that languages are at the forefront of the ranking tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a Higher A grade.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS schools that are members, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a Higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who study German, 69 percent of those who study French and 63 percent who study A Spanish also.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages are now, as a choice of subject, being kept in the same regard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that from reasons given by employers to having sent to fill vacancies, 17 per cent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more imperative in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more prospective job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career one chooses, if one learns another language, this will have a real advantage in the future as it will have the ability to survive such a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a multilingual person at the forefront of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation and, with 15 percent, French is the only language spoken with a two-digit percentage.
That's why investing in language learning is now important for today's children.
Knowing more than one language, particularly those of developing economies, children will have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will learn different languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills needed to be successful, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at present, in a global business environment, that languages remain very important for the country's future, and therefore this should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
The fat's not fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
